# Missionary Meta-Learning

Lessons from previous missionaries about strategy design, methodology choices, and what works at the strategic level. These lessons generalize across missions — they're about how to design effective strategies, not about specific domains.

## Entries

- [`strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md`](strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md) — Ground-clearing strategies for obstruction mapping. Phase 0 redefines targets, "adversarial → targeted test" is the strongest quality pattern, test generalization of mechanisms early, prescribe lead-pursuit phases. (vasseur-pressure, strategy-001, 2026-03-30)
- [`strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md`](strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md) — Dual-track obstruction+construction for impossibility proofs. Phase 0 decomposition audit is highest-leverage for proof-improvement missions; Direction Status Tracker enables clean stopping; two-strategy map→attack arc produces strongest impossibility results. (vasseur-pressure, strategy-002, 2026-03-31)

| File | Date | Summary |
|------|------|---------|
| `strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Three-phase derive-compute-adjudicate protocol for formula verification. Parallel Phase 1 is optimal. Mandate mission-critical explorations (don't leave experimental tests as optional). Best findings often emerge as side effects of stress-test fixes. Front-load computation. |
| `strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Constraint-catalog methodology for hard unsolved problems. Ground-clearing strategies produce Tier 2-3 results but not Tier 1 novelty. Make synthesis/adversarial phases mandatory with minimum allocations. Force constructive work (building operators), not just testing known ones. Prescribe data scale (millions of zeros, not thousands). |
| `strategy-001-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Reproduce→Extend→Stress-Test for computational missions. Survey explorations at the start pay for themselves. Pre-loading verified formulas compounds across explorations. Adversarial review should come early, not just at end. "Computation mandatory" was the single most important rule. First strategies should prioritize breadth over depth. |
| `strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Adversarial Derivation Protocol for hypothesis-testing missions. Dimensional analysis as Phase 1 gatekeeper saves entire budgets. Adversarial tests must come early (slot 3-4), not late (slot 8). Pre-launch algebra checks prevent trivially-doomed explorations. Side-effects of failures produce the most interesting findings. One strategy can be sufficient for binary yes/no missions. |
| `strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Probe-Attack-Synthesize for hard unsolved problems. First strategy = ground-clearing, second = constructive. Adversarial review must come early (slot 6-7), not at the end. Require math specificity in methodology. Quantitative negative results (AC bounds 57-69x vacuous) reach Tier 3; qualitative ones don't. Pre-load all prior findings into next strategy. |
| `strategy-002-classicality-budget-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Focused claim-deepening protocol after a survey strategy. All explorations mandatory (no optional). Second strategies should target specific gaps, not re-explore. Prescriptive literature search (specific papers + search terms) beats exploratory. Two-strategy arc (survey → deepen) may be default for formula-verification missions. |
| `strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Compute-first methodology for framework comparison missions. "Compute first" was wrong emphasis for structural/conceptual domains — surveys produced better results. Match methodology to domain type. Framework-comparison missions follow map→characterize→probe→synthesize arc. Novel claims from well-studied fields will be synthesis, not discovery. One strategy can suffice for clearly scoped questions. |
| `strategy-002-sed-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Parallel probes for frontier mapping. All three probes produced novel data (none wasted). Two-strategy arc (depth then breadth) is natural for computational missions. Physical constant verification must be a cross-phase rule. Adversarial review MUST find prior art or it hasn't done its job. Tunneling formula R²=0.9998 was the mission's strongest result — emerged from a "quick probe" design. |
| `strategy-002-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Tournament methodology for constructive research. Tournament→Deep Dive→Mandatory Adversarial is the best three-phase arc for constructive missions. Adversarial review is the highest-ROI phase — it caught two false claims. Construction strategies produce better novelty than testing strategies. Prescribe specific null-hypothesis control experiments. Explorer death rate (4/9) is the #1 operational problem. |
| `strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md` | 2026-03-28 | Focused-attack strategy for a quantitative gap. Check formula validity in target regime before making it the strategy centerpiece. Don't designate one computation as "the most important" — creates brittleness. Three-strategy arc has diminishing returns by strategy 3. Adversarial self-refutation chains (find→validate→refute) are the system's most honest output. 24 explorations across 3 strategies is the natural scale for hard problems. |
| `strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Phased foundation-then-comparison for hypothesis-testing. "Explorers must compute" was the single most important rule. Interpretation questions (local vs global) are blocking — resolve before computing consequences. Negative results in the obvious regime are efficient but leave interesting territory untouched. 4 explorations can suffice for a definitive conclusion. Pre-specify comparison baselines explicitly. |
| `strategy-003-sed-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Finishing strategy: 3+1 (parallel cleanup + adversarial synthesis). Full 3-strategy arc: depth→breadth→synthesis is natural for computational missions. Adversarial synthesis in finishing strategy is the most valuable exploration — catches overclaiming. Survey missions on well-studied topics have a natural Tier 3-4 ceiling. Budget 3 strategies upfront. Don't defer theoretical frameworks to the finishing strategy. |
| `strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Constructive attack producing novel rigorous result. Adversarial review (E007) after first surprise produced the most important finding (staggered mode tight bound). Original attack vector (RG+BE) correctly abandoned for simpler tighter analysis. 3-exploration proof arc (slack → tight bound → proof) is the natural unit. Prescribe methodology not attack vector — let strategizer pivot. β < 1/6 proved (4× state of art), β < 1/4 with one remaining inequality. |
| `strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md` | 2026-03-28 | Parallel computational probes for regime exploration. All-mandatory parallel probes + pre-loaded context is the highest-efficiency pattern. Adversarial review must be structurally enforced (not just labeled mandatory) — strategizer skipped it. Approximation caveats need built-in resolution paths. Early stopping at 3/10 explorations was mixed: results decisive but claims unverified. Physics errors in GOALs for QFT must specify which symmetry generator. |
| `strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md` | 2026-03-28 | Finishing strategy for verification and synthesis. Tight budget (4 mandatory, no early stopping) ensured adversarial review ran. 3-strategy arc (depth→breadth→synthesis) is the natural pattern for hypothesis-testing missions. Parameter sweeps are discovery machines (found spectrum-preservation discriminant). 11 explorations across 3 strategies is the natural scale. Adversarial review belongs in a finishing strategy where it can't be skipped. |
| `strategy-003-yang-mills-learnings.md` | 2026-03-28 | Proof tournament finishing strategy for closing one inequality. Parallel proof attempts eliminate false premises faster than sequential (found M(Q)≼M(I) FALSE in round 1). Finishing strategies should expect NOT to close the gap — value is in obstruction mapping. "Check X numerically before proving X" is mandatory. 30 explorations across 3 strategies is the natural scale for Millennium-adjacent problems. Obstruction atlases are a publishable contribution. |
| `strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md` | 2026-03-28 | Single-strategy framework analysis with pre-loaded adversarial context. Pre-loading adversarial findings from prior missions is the highest-leverage move for framework analysis — saves 1-2 explorations. One strategy suffices for well-scoped "is this X?" evaluation questions. Steelman requirement transforms adversarial reviews from dismissive to nuanced. For reformulation missions, explicitly require a "what computation would upgrade this to new physics?" exploration. 6 explorations in 1 strategy is the natural scale for evaluation missions. |
| `strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md` | 2026-03-28 | Adversarial proof audit for validation missions. Adversarial posture is the single most important rule — it found a genuine proof gap. "Independent rederivation" can reproduce known errors if conventions aren't pinned. Convention verification deserves its own exploration. Numerical extensions as Phase 2 are robust because they're independent of proof gaps. Validation missions are 1-2 strategy affairs. 8 explorations with 190+ configs, 0 violations. |
| `strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md` | 2026-03-29 | Focused gap repair with check-before-prove methodology. Stress tests need systematic TYPE coverage (all-link/single-link × large/small angle), not just volume — 300 configs missed a violation that systematic types caught. 3/5-6 budget used for definitive negative result. Novel permanent results (analytical Hessian formula) can emerge from failed repairs. Two-strategy validation arc (audit → repair attempt) is the natural pattern. Early termination on negative results saves budget. |
| `strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md` | 2026-03-28 | Three-phase decompose-construct-verify for proof problems. Parallel Phase 1 decompositions all contributed. ONE approach per proof exploration (never three — causes thinking paralysis). Combined Bound Lemma discovered computationally, not algebraically — validates "compute first." Failed explorations have downstream value. Strategizer's best decisions were deviations from the strategy. 8/10 budget, partial proof + precise gap characterization. |
| `strategy-002-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md` | 2026-03-29 | Upstream logic verification must precede proof construction. Proved full 9D staggered bound via affine-in-D + Cauchy-Schwarz, but staggered bound doesn't imply full conjecture — non-staggered eigenvalues uncontrolled. "Wrong target" is the costliest failure mode (wastes entire strategies, not just explorations). Mandatory Phase 0: verify that proof target implies desired conclusion. ONE approach per exploration strongly validated. Formula cross-checking against source paper is essential. |
